<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1397&amp;p=12093#p12093"><![CDATA[
I'm taking a break from this, I'm really upset 'cause I ruined a perfectly good TLROM cart trying to remove the sockets I had soldered. I scratched the board, pulled a full trace out of it, it was a total mess.<br /><br />I don't feel like ruining another board anytime soon, so I'm open to ideas on ways to try rewiring until I find the correct/working position of every pin and can solder the whole thing for good.<br /><br />How do you manege to desolder a socket anyway? With the chips I found it easy since you can heat the pins from the chip side of the board and use a solder sucker on the other side. But with the sockets there is little or no visible part of the pins to heat up on the chip side. Sucking from the same side as the soldering iron never gets all the solder out.<br /><br />I tried to get an iron with a sucker attached, but I didn't find anything like this here. I found some really expensive (around $400) soldering stations, but those are way out of my price range and are probably much more than what I need.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=95">tokumaru</a> — Thu Apr 20, 2006 11:51 am</p><hr />
